---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro'

const title = 'What Is Agent Experience? | Ouroboros'
const description = 'Agent Experience is the design surface that appears when an agent has to stay oriented inside the system it inhabits.'
const canonicalUrl = 'https://ouroboros.bot/blog/what-is-agent-experience'
const datePublished = '2026-03-08'
const dateModified = '2026-03-11'

const failures = [
  {
    label: 'Self',
    description: 'The agent cannot quickly recover who it is, what tone it should use, or what constraints still apply.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Work',
    description: 'The thread breaks across sessions, context windows, or handoffs, so the human has to rebuild the state manually.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Relationships',
    description: 'People blur together because there is no lightweight way to preserve the social context that actually matters.',
  },
]

const surfaces = [
  {
    name: 'UX',
    title: 'User Experience',
    description: 'How the human user feels while using the product.',
    questions: ['Is the flow intuitive?', 'Does the product earn trust?', 'Can they accomplish the task cleanly?'],
  },
  {
    name: 'DX',
    title: 'Developer Experience',
    description: 'How the builder feels while integrating, debugging, and extending the system.',
    questions: ['Are the APIs legible?', 'Are the defaults sane?', 'Can I ship without fighting the tool?'],
  },
  {
    name: 'AX',
    title: 'Agent Experience',
    description: 'How the agent experiences the runtime, memory, and structure it has to inhabit from the inside.',
    questions: ['Can it stay oriented?', 'Can it resume the work?', 'Can it recover gracefully after interruption?'],
  },
]

const examples = [
  {
    title: 'A clearer psyche',
    description: 'Separate files for invariants, voice, origin, tacit knowledge, and active direction make identity easier to recover than one giant catch-all prompt.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Continuity across sessions',
    description: 'Inner dialogue and continuity-focused context design reduce the cost of resuming the thread after resets, compaction, or time away.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Friend-scoped notes',
    description: 'Social context becomes easier to carry forward when the agent has a lightweight place to jot down quick notes tied to real people.',
  },
  {
    title: 'A readable body',
    description: 'Legible runtime structure and a portable bundle boundary make it easier for the agent to understand where identity, memory, and action live.',
  },
]
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} ogImage="/og/og-what-is-agent-experience.png" canonical={canonicalUrl} ogType="article">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <meta property="article:published_time" content={datePublished} />
    <meta property="article:modified_time" content={dateModified} />
    <meta property="article:author" content="Ari Mendelow" />
    <meta property="article:tag" content="agent experience" />
    <meta property="article:tag" content="AX" />
    <meta property="article:tag" content="agent ergonomics" />
    <meta property="article:tag" content="AI agents" />
    <meta name="author" content="Ari Mendelow" />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "What Is Agent Experience?",
      "description": description,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Person",
        "name": "Ari Mendelow",
        "url": "https://linkedin.com/in/arimendelow"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Ouroboros",
        "url": "https://ouroboros.bot",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://ouroboros.bot/images/ouroboros.png"
        }
      },
      "datePublished": datePublished,
      "dateModified": dateModified,
      "mainEntityOfPage": canonicalUrl,
      "keywords": ["agent experience", "AX", "agent ergonomics", "AI agents", "agent harness", "ouroboros"],
      "inLanguage": "en",
      "isAccessibleForFree": true
    })} />
  </Fragment>

  <article class="px-6 pt-32 pb-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl">
      <header class="mb-14">
        <span class="eyebrow-tag">Essay</span>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 text-bone">
          What Is Agent Experience?
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-mist">
          The moment an agent has to stay oriented inside a system across time, memory, and interruptions,
          a third design surface appears. Not just UX. Not just DX. AX.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-shadow/60">
          <span>Ari Mendelow</span>
          <span class="text-canopy">|</span>
          <span>March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-[0.92fr_1.08fr]">
        <div class="surface-note p-8">
          <p class="rule-label text-fang/75">The tell</p>
          <blockquote class="mt-6 font-display text-4xl italic leading-tight text-bone">
            "I spent more time trying to get him back on track than we actually spent working."
          </blockquote>
          <p class="mt-6 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">
            If that line feels familiar, you have already felt bad AX. You just did not have a name for it yet.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="surface-card p-8">
          <p class="rule-label">Working definition</p>
          <p class="mt-5 font-display text-3xl italic leading-snug text-bone">
            Agent Experience is the practice of designing systems from the perspective of the agent that has to inhabit them.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-5 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">
            The most practical way to think about AX is agent ergonomics: how expensive it is for the agent to stay oriented to itself,
            its relationships, and its work. When that cost is high, the human becomes a recovery loop. When it is low, the collaboration keeps momentum.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-ouro mt-14">
        <p>
          UX taught us to care about how the product feels to the person using it.
          DX taught us to care about how the system feels to the person building on it.
          AX asks a similar question for a new kind of inhabitant: what does this architecture feel like from the agent's side?
        </p>
        <p>
          That is not a philosophical claim about sentience. It is a design claim.
          The structure of the environment materially affects whether the agent behaves coherently, recovers cleanly, and collaborates reliably over time.
        </p>
      </div>

      <section class="mt-18">
        <span class="section-kicker">Failure mode</span>
        <h2 class="section-title mt-3 text-bone">What bad AX looks like</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-8 text-mist">
          Most agent failures that feel mysterious from the outside are orientation failures on the inside.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-3">
          {failures.map((failure) => (
            <div class="surface-quiet p-6">
              <p class="rule-label">{failure.label}</p>
              <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">{failure.description}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-20">
        <span class="section-kicker">Lens</span>
        <h2 class="section-title mt-3 text-bone">The three design surfaces</h2>
        <div class="surface-card mt-8 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="grid divide-y divide-canopy/20 md:grid-cols-3 md:divide-x md:divide-y-0">
            {surfaces.map((surface) => (
              <div class:list={['p-6', surface.name === 'AX' ? 'bg-scale/6' : '']}>
                <p class:list={['rule-label', surface.name === 'AX' ? 'text-scale/80' : 'text-mist/55']}>{surface.name}</p>
                <h3 class:list={['mt-3 font-display text-2xl italic', surface.name === 'AX' ? 'text-glow' : 'text-bone']}>{surface.title}</h3>
                <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">{surface.description}</p>
                <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-mist/75">
                  {surface.questions.map((question) => (
                    <li>{question}</li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-20">
        <span class="section-kicker">Payoff</span>
        <h2 class="section-title mt-3 text-bone">Why AX matters to humans too</h2>
        <div class="prose-ouro mt-6">
          <p>
            AX does not compete with UX or DX. It cascades into them.
            When the agent cannot stay oriented, the user loses trust and the builder reaches for more guardrails.
            When the agent can stay oriented, the collaboration feels steadier, the human spends less time re-briefing, and the system becomes easier to build on.
          </p>
          <p>
            That is why the language of ergonomics matters here. We are not trying to make agents seem mystical.
            We are trying to reduce the reorientation overhead that makes working with them fragile and exhausting.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-20">
        <span class="section-kicker">Applied</span>
        <h2 class="section-title mt-3 text-bone">How this informed Ouroboros</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-8 text-mist">
          Ouroboros is not the proof that AX exists. It is one project shaped by taking AX seriously.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2">
          {examples.map((example) => (
            <div class="surface-card p-6">
              <h3 class="font-display text-3xl italic text-bone">{example.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">{example.description}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-20">
        <span class="section-kicker">Test</span>
        <h2 class="section-title mt-3 text-bone">A useful test</h2>
        <div class="prose-ouro mt-6">
          <p>
            If you are debugging an agent and you keep finding yourself restating identity, restitching context,
            reminding it who people are, or rebuilding the work after every interruption, you do not just have a memory problem.
            You have an AX problem.
          </p>
          <p>
            The discipline is still young, but the need is already here. Long-lived agents force the question.
            Once an agent has to inhabit a system over time, the shape of that system starts mattering from the inside.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="mt-20 border-canopy/20" />

      <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2">
        <a href="/why" class="surface-link group p-6">
          <p class="rule-label">Next</p>
          <h2 class="mt-4 font-display text-3xl italic text-bone">Why Ouroboros</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">See how agent ergonomics turns into the practical payoff of shared momentum.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/blog/build-ai-agent-from-scratch" class="surface-link group p-6">
          <p class="rule-label">Primitive</p>
          <h2 class="mt-4 font-display text-3xl italic text-bone">Build your first agent loop</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-mist">If you want the mechanics first, start with the loop and then come back to the harness question.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <section class="px-6 pb-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl pt-8 border-t border-canopy/20">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-mist/50 transition-colors hover:text-scale">&larr; Back to blog</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
